\@writefile{lof}{\contentsline {figure}{\numberline {3.2}{\ignorespaces Coupling matrices with their prescribed marginals. The central grayscale image displays $\mathrm  {P}_{ij}$; the red curve on the left is the source marginal $\mathrm  {a}$, and the blue curve on top is the target marginal $\mathrm  {b}$. The independent product plan is diffuse, whereas the one-dimensional optimal plan concentrates near the monotone quantile correspondence. Only the dense 200-bin optimal panel overlays the barycentric projection $i\DOTSB \mapstochar \rightarrow \DOTSI \sumop \slimits@ _j \mathrm  {P}_{ij}j/\mathrm  {a}_i$, because that curve is meaningful visually only at sufficient resolution.}}{30}{figure.3.2}\protected@file@percent }
\newlabel{fig:kantorovich-coupling-matrix-marginals}{{3.2}{30}{Coupling matrices with their prescribed marginals. The central grayscale image displays $\P _{ij}$; the red curve on the left is the source marginal $\a $, and the blue curve on top is the target marginal $\b $. The independent product plan is diffuse, whereas the one-dimensional optimal plan concentrates near the monotone quantile correspondence. Only the dense 200-bin optimal panel overlays the barycentric projection $i\mapsto \sum _j \P _{ij}j/\a _i$, because that curve is meaningful visually only at sufficient resolution}{figure.3.2}{}}
